context: The <a0_0><b5_0>1903<b5_0/><a0_0/> advent of heavier-than-air fixed-wing aircraft was closely followed in <a1_0><b6_0>1910<b6_0/><a1_0/> by the first experimental take-off of an airplane, made from the deck of a United States Navy vessel (cruiser USS Birmingham), and the first experimental landings were conducted in <a2_0><b7_0>1911<b7_0/><a2_0/>. On 9 May 1912 the first airplane take-off from a ship underway was made from the deck of the British Royal Navy's HMS Hibernia. Seaplane tender support ships came next, with the French Foudre of 1911. In September 1914 the Imperial Japanese Navy Wakamiya conducted <a3_0><b8_0>the world's first successful ship-launched air raid<b8_0/><a3_0/>: on 6 September 1914 a Farman aircraft launched by Wakamiya attacked the Austro-Hungarian cruiser SMS Kaiserin Elisabeth and the German gunboat Jaguar in Kiaochow Bay off Tsingtao; neither was hit. The first carrier-launched airstrike was <a4_0>the <b9_0>Tondern Raid in July 1918<b9_0/><a4_0/>. Seven Sopwith Camels launched from the converted battlecruiser HMS Furious damaged the German airbase at Tønder and destroyed two zeppelins.
